Step 4: Summarize data by date and Type

df$date_label <- as.factor(df$created_date)   # dates as categorical data. 
df$Type <- as.factor(df$Type) # The 'Type' column as categorical data

## Summarize data by date and Type
daily_count <- df %>% 
  group_by(date_label, Type) %>%  #group the dataset by the two columns: date_label and Type
  summarise(avg_totalinteractions = mean(`Total Interactions`),
            avg_likes = mean(Likes), #get the average of like counts
            avg_comments = mean(Comments),# get the average of comment count
            avg_followercount = mean(`Followers at Posting`),
            post_count = length(unique(URL))) #get the total unique post count per day and per type 

daily_count <- daily_count %>% pivot_longer(cols = -c(date_label, Type), names_to = "variable", values_to = "value") #convert daily_count to a long form.

datatable(daily_count[1:25,], )  #display the data frame and show the first 25 rows.

Look at the newly created dataframe object called daily_count and explain how the numbers are generated.

Step 5: Use ggplot2 to plot daily counts by Type

daily_count$date_label <- as.Date(daily_count$date_label) ## in order for the dates to be plotted, the date_label column must be converted back to Date

ggplot(data = daily_count[daily_count$variable=="post_count",], aes(x = date_label, y = value, group = Type)) + ##this shows data points whose value on the variable column matches "post_count"   
  geom_line(linewidth = 0.6, alpha = 1.7, aes(color = Type)) +
  geom_point(size = 1) +
  ylim(0, NA) +
  theme(legend.title=element_blank(), axis.title.x = element_blank()) +
  ylab("add your Y axis here") + 
  ggtitle("add your title here") +
  theme_fivethirtyeight(base_size = 12, base_family = "sans")

Step 6: Use highcharter for interactive plotting

library(highcharter)

title <- paste0("Daily total interactions ", Sys.Date())
highchart() %>%
  hc_add_series(daily_count[daily_count$variable=="avg_totalinteractions",],"line", hcaes(x = date_label, y = value,group=Type)) %>%
  hc_xAxis(type = "datetime")

Step 7: Use Prophet for forecasting

An optional task for COMM students, but required for DACSS students.

More on prophet, the automated forecasting algorithm made by Meta: https://facebook.github.io/prophet/

library(prophet)

forcase <- df[,c("date_label","Likes")] #create a subset dataframe to include only the date column and the column that indicates an engagement outcome
colnames(forcase) <-c("ds","y") #change the column names to fit the requirement of the prophet library

m <- prophet(forcase, weekly.seasonality=TRUE) #make forecast! 
future <- make_future_dataframe(m, periods = 365) 
forecast <- predict(m, future) #make prediction! 

prophet_plot_components(m, forecast) #plot the outcome
